And in the like spirit we must receive the exhortations of the Apostles to slaves, except that these seem rather to exhort them to obedience while they are slaves, which is agreeable to natural equity3 for aliment and work done have a natural correspondence.

VII. But I think that another precept of the theologians whom I have begun to speak of is right: that a slave cannot, without violating the duty of justice, resist the master in the execution of that external right. For between this case and the other, there is a manifest disÎ‡ crepance. The external right, which consists not only in the impu- nity of the act, but is the protection of the right by the judicial tribu- nals, is void if the right of resisting on the opposite side remain. For isit be lawful to resist the master by force, it will be lawful to resist the magistrate who protects the master3 and yet the magistrate, by the Law of Nations, ought to defend the master in his ownership and its exercise.
